Propensity Score Matching With Average Treatment Effect (TWANG package)

Anahita Kumar

2023-03-16

overview: PSM using average treatment effect (TWANG package), followed by causal inference using the matched dataset as a robustness check of results from an unmatched dataset.

1 Sample Code and Statistical Output

This document provides the code and output for a part of the analysis of an experimental intervention conducted in Mumbai, India. The project was a pre-registered trial, and the manuscript detailing the findings is currently under peer review for academic publication. The author, as the principal investigator of this study, conceptualized the program design, oversaw its implementation, and conducted all statistical analyses.

parents_comparison <- parents_comparison %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(starts_with("M")), ~ na_if(., 88)) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(starts_with("G"), -ends_with("5")), ~ na_if(., 88)) %>% 
  select(everything())

parents_endline_data <- read.csv("parents_endline_data.csv")
parents_endline_data$ID <- parents_endline_data$A01

parents_endline_data <- parents_endline_data %>% 
  select(starts_with("V"), "ID") %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(starts_with("V"), -ends_with("8")), ~ na_if(., 88)) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(starts_with("V"), -ends_with("8")), ~ na_if(., 99))

parents_comparison <- parents_comparison %>%
  inner_join(parents_endline_data, by = "ID")

Procedure based on https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/twang/vignettes/twang.pdf, following the Typical workflow with twang (section 2.4).

  1. Determine the estimand of interest, either ATE or ATT. We choose to estimate the ATE (average treatment effect).

  2. Determine the observed confounding factors to be balanced. Already determined, C2 = parent age C4 = child age C5 = marital status N01 = parent school aspiration N02 = parent school expectation discipline = harsh discipline practices food_before_covid = food insecurity pre-covid food_during_covid = food insecurity during covid support_z = parent support, standardized A04 = school stratification A08 = child gender

  3. Fit the propensity score model using the ps() function.

  • Evaluate the convergence of the algorithm.
  • Assess the balance of the confounding factors before and after applying the propensity score weights.
  • If needed, rerun the algorithm adjusting the gradient boosting parameters to achieve convergence or improve balance.
## This is lavaan 0.6-19
## lavaan is FREE software! Please report any bugs.

The saved object psm_test1 is of class ps and contains the propensity score model fit information. We will work with this object to assess model convergence, to assess the balance of pretreatment characteristics, and to extract the propensity score weights needed for subsequent analysis. By default, the ps() function uses the gbm package for gradient boosting. A user can request use of xgboost by specifying the option version=“xgboost”. The use of xgboost is not be discussed further in the tutorial we used. See the documentation for additional details.

2 Running Diagnostic Tests

As a default, the plot() function applied to a ps object gives the balance measures as a function of the number of iterations in the gradient boosting algorithm, with higher iterations corresponding to more complicated fitted models. This figure also gives information on how compatible two or more stopping rules are: if the minima for multiple stopping rules under consideration are near one another, the results should not be sensitive to which stopping rule one uses for the final analysis.

3 Assessing balance using balance tables

Having estimated the propensity scores, bal.table() produces a table that shows how well the resulting weights succeed in manipulating the control group so that its weighted pretreatment characteristics match, or balance, those of the unweighted treatment group when estimand = “ATT”. If estimand = “ATE”, both the control and treatment groups are weighted so that the weighted pretreatment characteristics match, or balance, with one another. By default, the bal.table() function uses the value of estimand set with the ps() function call. For example, in the analysis we set estimand = “ATT” when calling ps() to estimate the propensity scores. The function bal.table() automatically uses the correct weights when checking balance and comparing the distributions of pre-treatment variables for the weighted control group with those from the unweighted treatment group.

psm_balance <- bal.table(psm_test1)

The ESS is approximately the number of observations from a simple random sample that yields an estimate with sampling variation equal to the sampling variation obtained with the weighted comparison observations. Therefore, the ESS will give an estimate of the number of comparison participants that are comparable to the treatment group when estimand = “ATT”. The ESS is an accurate measure of the relative size of the variance of means when the weights are fixed or they are uncorrelated with outcomes. Otherwise the ESS underestimates the effective sample size (Little & Vartivarian, 2004). With propensity score weights, it is rare that weights are uncorrelated with outcomes. Hence the ESS typically gives a lower bound on the effective sample size, but it still serves as a useful measure for choosing among alternative models and assessing the overall quality of a model, even if it provides a possibly conservative picture of the loss in precision due to weighting. The ess.treat and ess.ctrl columns in the summary results shows the ESS for the estimated propensity scores. Note that although the original comparison group had 244 cases, the propensity score estimates effectively utilize only 88 or 90 of the comparison cases, depending on the rules and measures used to estimate the propensity score. Since the estimand of interest in this example is ATT, ess.treat = n.treat throughout (i.e., all treatment cases have a weight of 1).

4 Graphical assessments of balance

Specifying plots = 2 or plots = “boxplot” produces boxplots illustrating the spread of the estimated propensity scores in the treatment and comparison groups. Whereas propensity score stratification requires considerable overlap in these spreads, excellent covariate balance can often be achieved with weights, even when the propensity scores estimated for the treatment and control groups show little overlap.

plot(psm_test1, plots = 2)

The effect size plot illustrates the effect of weights on the magnitude of differences between groups on each pretreatment covariate. These magnitudes are standardized using the standardized effect size described earlier. In these plots, substantial reductions in effect sizes are observed for all variables (blue lines). Closed red circles indicate a statistically significant difference, many of which occur before weighting, only one after. ES plot below:

plot(psm_test1, plots = 3)

When many of the p-values testing individual covariates for balance are very small, the groups are clearly imbalanced and inconsistent with what we would expect had the groups been formed by random assignment. After weighting we would expect the p-values to be larger if balance had been achieved. We use a QQ plot comparing the quantiles of the observed p-values to the quantiles of the uniform distribution (45 degree line) to conduct this check of balance. Ideally, the p-values from independent tests in which the null hypothesis is true will have a uniform distribution. Although the ideal is unlikely to hold even if we had random assignment (Bland, 2013), severe deviation of the p-values below the diagonal suggests lack of balance and p-values running at or above the diagonal suggests balance might have been achieved. The p-value plot (plots=4 or plots=“t”) allows users to visually to inspect the p-values of the t-tests for group differences in the covariate means. Our results are not great, but one can see they approach the diagonal distrbution.

Before weighting (closed circles), the groups have statistically significant differences on many variables (i.e., p-values are near zero). After weighting (open circles) the p-values are generally slightly below the 45-degree line, which represents the cumulative distribution of a uniform variable on [0,1]. This indicates that the p-values are slightly lower than would be expected in a randomized study.

plot(psm_test1, plots = 4)

One can inspect similar plots for the KS statistic, which in this case is better:

plot(psm_test1, plots = 5)

The gbm package has various tools for exploring the relationship between the covariates and the treatment assignment indicator if these are of interest. These tools can be used with the ps object to extract useful information. In particular, the summary() function applied to the underling gbm object computes the relative influence of each variable for estimating the probability of treatment assignment. The relaive influence of each variable changes as more iteration are added to the gradient boosted model. In this example, we choose the number of iterations to be the optimal number for minimizing the largest of the KS statistics. This value can be found in the ps.lalonde.gbm\(desc\)ks.max.ATT$n.trees. Figure 1 shows the barchart of the relative influence and is produced when plot=TRUE in the call to summary().

# Function to add stars based on significance levels
add_significance_stars <- function(cor_matrix, p_values) {
  stars <- ifelse(is.na(p_values), "",  # Replace NA with empty string
           ifelse(p_values < 0.001, "***", 
           ifelse(p_values < 0.01, "**", 
           ifelse(p_values < 0.05, "*", ""))))
  
  # Combine the correlation values with significance stars
  cor_with_stars <- matrix(paste(round(cor_matrix, 2), stars, sep=""), 
                           nrow = nrow(cor_matrix), ncol = ncol(cor_matrix))
  rownames(cor_with_stars) <- rownames(cor_matrix)
  colnames(cor_with_stars) <- colnames(cor_matrix)
  
  return(cor_with_stars)
}

# Apply the function
cor_with_stars <- add_significance_stars(cor_matrix, p_values)

# View the correlation matrix with stars
print(cor_with_stars)

# Function to add stars based on significance levels
add_significance_stars <- function(cor_matrix2, p_values2) {
  stars <- ifelse(is.na(p_values2), "",  # Replace NA with empty string
           ifelse(p_values2 < 0.001, "***", 
           ifelse(p_values2 < 0.01, "**", 
           ifelse(p_values2 < 0.05, "*", ""))))
  
  # Combine the correlation values with significance stars
  cor_with_stars <- matrix(paste(round(cor_matrix2, 2), stars, sep=""), 
                           nrow = nrow(cor_matrix2), ncol = ncol(cor_matrix2))
  rownames(cor_with_stars) <- rownames(cor_matrix2)
  colnames(cor_with_stars) <- colnames(cor_matrix2)
  
  return(cor_with_stars)
}

# Apply the function
cor_with_stars <- add_significance_stars(cor_matrix2, p_values2)

# View the correlation matrix with stars
print(cor_with_stars)
